We recommended and the LCE concurred to require the: 

(a) Municipal Engineer to 

(i) determine and address the cause of the deficiencies pertaining to detailed engineering; 

(ii) ensure the completion of the projects within the time frame specified in the contract and take appropriate action against the erring contractor, as warranted; 

(iii) provide the Audit Team with the necessary documents that will support time extension due to Extra Work Order; and 

(iv) submit an explanation on the cost of un-complied COSH Programs; 

(b) BAC and TWG to 

(i) undertake bidding and award only after the detailed engineering for the project had been sufficiently carried out as provided in IRR of RA 9184; 

(ii) scrutinize the sufficiency of the contractor’s manpower on all the projects in the post-qualification stage of the procurement process; and 

(c) Municipal Accountant to ensure that the required documents are attached to the Disbursement Vouchers before processing of payments.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to: 

(a) expedite the construction of sanitary landfill to unburden the barangays of managing their own garbage within their areas;

(b) strictly enforce and intensify compliance with the Municipal Ordinances particularly on no littering policy among the residents; 

(c) recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of RA No. 9003 and; 

(e) consider imposing fines and penalties for violators of the Anti-Littering policy as well as filing of administrative cases against erring government officials as provided by Sections 49 and 50 of RA No. 9003.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the 

(a) Municipal Accountant to 

(i) coordinate with the concerned bank officials to determine the facts surrounding the closure of the three bank accounts, based on which, take action in accordance with relevant regulations; 

(ii) exert extra efforts in locating the documents supporting the reconciling items including the stale checks, and adjust books as warranted; 

(iii) henceforth immediately take up in the books any cash reconciling item identified; and 

(b) Municipal Treasurer to send written notice to the payees at least one month before the checks become stale.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to: 

(a) find ways how to comply with the prescribed physical validation and reporting procedures for PPE with consideration of health requirements during the COVID-19 pandemic; 
(b) instruct the Municipal Assessor and Designated General Services Officer to facilitate the titling of the four parcels of land in the Municipality name; 

(c) require the designated General Service Officer and Municipal Accountant to 

(i) ensure that all government property officially acquired by the Municipality are accounted for and taken up in the books; 

(ii) provide proof of ownership on the 31 vehicles as identified in audits; and 

(iii) see to it that all its motor vehicles are registered annually with the LTO and placed under GSIS insurance coverage.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the 

(a) General Services Officer to 

(i) perform the duties and responsibilities mandated under Section 490 (b) of the Local Government Code RA 7160

(ii) render report on the donations received by her Office; 

(b) Head, Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Office (MDRRMO) to furnish the Accounting Office and Committee on Physical Inventory of PPE, a copy of Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM and Acknowledgement Receipts for In-kind Donations for DRRM as bases of recording in the agency’s books and reports; 

(c) Municipal Accountant to 

(i) record In-kind Donations received; 

(ii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements of information pertaining to DRRM particularly on the quantity of donated relief goods received, issued and balance as well as the receipt of donated PPE (if any) and its disposal/transfer; and 
(d) Committee on Physical Inventory of PPE to include those In-kind Donations received by the municipality in the physical count and render its corresponding Inventory Report.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the 

(a) GFPS Executive Committee to continue its efforts in adhering to the provisions of the Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 dated January 15, 2013 and; 

(b) Municipal Planning Development Office Head to monitor the status of maintenance/updating the GAD database.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to 

(a) invest on its personnel in the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Office by providing the current officer with at least the necessary seminar/training as required in the manual; 

(b) prioritize the procurement of disaster related equipment and;

We recommended and management agreed to:

(a) 	give sufficient budget for SWM and hasten the expropriation of land for SWM Facility; 

(b) 	expedite the collaboration with the nearby municipalities for the construction of shared sanitary landfill which is also currently under evaluation by LGU-Casiguran and LGU-Dinalungan; 

(c) 	require the SWM Board, in collaboration with the Sangguniang Bayan to formulate and enact an SWM ordinance particularly promoting, among others, Section 10 of R.A. No. 9003; 

(d) 	ensure full compliance of the barangays to the SWM ordinance and encourage the community to participate to that cause; 

(f) 	consider creation of a plantilla position whose functions will focus on the planning, implementation and monitoring of solid waste management of the municipality.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

(a) 	instruct the Accountant to impose liquidated damages upon the contractor for the unjustified delays in contract implementation;

(b) 	direct the Municipal Engineer to 

(i) explain why the contractor was allowed time extensions with no justifiable basis; 

(ii) recommend appropriate actions in case of infractions of contract and approved program specifications; and 

(iii) henceforth conduct timely monitoring and evaluation of the work accomplishment in accordance with the project schedule;

(c)  	require the BAC to demand from the contractors, Warranty Security as required under Section 62 of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to protect the interest of the LGU; and

(d) 	appoint the Municipal Treasurer to serve as "provisional" member instead of being part of the "regular" member of the BAC whenever the procurement involves her unit she being the end-user of the items subject of the bidding.

We recommended and management agreed to:

(a) 	give sufficient budget for SWM and hasten the expropriation of land for SWM Facility; 

(b) 	expedite the collaboration with the nearby municipalities for the construction of shared sanitary landfill which is also currently under evaluation by LGU-Casiguran and LGU-Dinalungan; 

(c) 	require the SWM Board, in collaboration with the Sangguniang Bayan to formulate and enact an SWM ordinance particularly promoting, among others, Section 10 of R.A. No. 9003; 

(d) 	ensure full compliance of the barangays to the SWM ordinance and encourage the community to participate to that cause; 

(e) 	constantly review, update and revise the 10-year SWM Plan and seek approval from EMB to be able to fully implement R.A. No. 9003 for the optimum management of the municipality's solid waste; and 

(f) 	consider creation of a plantilla position whose functions will focus on the planning, implementation and monitoring of solid waste management of the municipality.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) cause the immediate development and operation of a sanitary landfill as the final waste disposal; 

(c) provide the necessary legislative support in the implementation of waste segregation at source, composting, recycling and applicable control measures on waste management.

