We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) cause the sending of demand letters to the concerned accountable officers for the immediate liquidation of their accountabilities including those who are no longer connected with the LGU; 

(b)  require the concerned personnel to liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose thereof has been accomplished; 

(c) withhold salaries of accountable officers who fail to effect prompt liquidation of their outstanding cash advances; and 

(d) institute appropriate administrative proceedings in case of non-compliance.

We recommended and the management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) instruct the (i) Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) to indicate in the 20% Development Plan timelines for the implementation of development projects/programs/activities; 

(ii) heads of implementing offices to expedite the implementation and completion of development projects that were not yet started/completed as at December 31, 2017; 

(b) create a project monitoring committee that will (i) closely monitor the implementation of the development projects; and (ii) report to the Local Chief Executive any deviations noted; and 

(c) henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of Section 5 of the DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017.

We also recommended that the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to 

(a) surrender and present all accountable forms not presented during the cash examination and remit the corresponding collections; 

(b) direct all accountable officers to adhere to the policy of daily remittance or turn-over of their collections and remit all the unremitted collections to the Liquidating Officer; 

(c) adjust the errors noted in the cashbook to reflect the correct cashbook balance; 

(d) adhere to the guideline that all transactions shall be personally recorded by the Accountable Officer in the cashbook; 

(e) stop the practice of allowing other person to record transaction/s in your cashbook; and 

(f) require all collecting officers to obtain a Fidelity Bond Certificate from Bureau of Treasury.

We recommended that Members of the Municipal Local School Board: 

(a) prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerned efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and stop the practice of accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute; 

(b) request for inputs from the DepEdOfficial/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures; 

(c) maximize the ultilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the Projects Program Activities (PPA's), and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprogramming, if necessary.

We reiterated our prior year's recommendation to: 

(a) send demand letter to the concerned accountable officers for the immediate liquidation of their accountabilities including those who are no longer connected with the LGU; 

(b) stop the practice of granting new cash advances without the liquidation of the previous accountability and require the concerned personnel to liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose thereof has been accomplished; 

(c) withhold salaries of accountable officers who fail to effect prompt liquidation of their outstanding cash advances; and 

(d) institute appropriate administrative proceedings in case of no-compliance.

We recommend that the

(a) Disaster Risk Reduction Management (DRRM) Officer regularly monitor and evaluate the utilization of Local Disater Risk Reduction Management Fund (LDRRMP); 

(b) Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to stop processing claims not related to disater preparation, mitigation and preparedness; 

(c) DRRM and Municipal Accountant prepare and submit regularly the report on sources and utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each month.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor 

(a) ensure the full or optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund during the budget year; 

(b) instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) to abide strictly with the guidelines in the formulation of the 20% Development Plan; 

(c) instruct the responsible officers to revert or reprogram the fund from unimplemented projects which are not among those enumerated to be chargeable to 20% DF and reprogram the same for qualified items and; 

(d) direct the members of the BAC to schedule early all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave way for their timely implementation and completion.

We recommended that the Head of Agency 

(a) require the Accountable Officer to restitute immediately the missing funds; 

(b) file appropriate charges against the erring Accountable Officer if circumstances warrant; 

(c) withhold the salary or any money due to the Accountable Officer in satisfaction of his shortage; 

(d) relieve of the defaulting Accountable Officer from his duties as ICO-Municipal Treasurer; 

(e) transfer him to the position where money accountability is not involve; 

(f) direct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to deposit intact and regularly all collections to its authorized depository bank pursuant to COA Circular No. 92-382 as well as future collections; 

(g) require the defaulting ICO-Municipal Treasurer to explain in writing why he failed to deposit his collections regularly and intact to its depository bank; 

(h) direct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of using the collections to pay various disbursements of the Municipality; and 

(i) require the Municipal Accountant and the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to make monthly reconciliation of their subsidiary ledger and cashbook balances so that whatever differences/ deficiencies could be adjusted immediately.

We also recommended that the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to 

(a) surrender and present all accountable forms not presented during the cash examination and remit the corresponding collections; 

(b) direct all accountable officers to adhere to the policy of daily remittance or turn-over of their collections and remit all the unremitted collections to the Liquidating Officer; 

(c) adjust the errors noted in the cashbook to reflect the correct cashbook balance; 

(d) adhere to the guideline that all transactions shall be personally recorded by the Accountable Officer in the cashbook; 

(e) stop the practice of allowing other person to record transaction/s in your cashbook; and 

(f) require all collecting officers to obtain a Fidelity Bond Certificate from Bureau of Treasury.
